metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #105
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: XYZ: Future Paths #3
metadata.description:
XYZ: Future Paths arises by exploring the use of a "random walker" algorithm through a three-dimensional coordinate space. In a way it is a continuation of my previous works "Contraformas" and "Similarity".

The principle of emergence can occur through the combination of the following factors: number of paths, movement pattern of the walker, the separation of the paths from each other, the length and minimum of each path, the frequency with which these variables change, the position of the camera in the z axis, the decrease in the size of the boxes, whether or not the boxes have borders, the size of the borders, the color of the palette, the range of variation of the color, the distance of the lights for each box, and some other rules.

3 available aspect ratios
2400 pixels high
More than 40 color palettes
3 canvas color styles
2 styles of boxes

Press "S" to save a png image
Press "T" to save a tiff image (may take time, canvastotiff.js)

created by @mdollinger using p5js

metadata.name: Kumano (Emergent Structures 1) #118
metadata.description:
"Kumano (Emergent Structures 1)" is a collection of generative works that emulate analog effects from painting, printmaking, and textile design. It is the first generative collection in a continuing series called Emergent Structures.

The title of this collection is borrowed from Kumano-zome (熊野染め), a traditional Japanese craft of resist-dyed fabric that creates beautiful analog interference patterns (moiré). These textiles, often rendered in tones of indigo dye, date back at least two hundred years, and yet they can feel magically modern. 

The primary structure of "Kumano" is a mesh of overlapping angled lines that function just like the hand-printed lines in Kumano-zome textiles.

My background is in abstract painting, and one of my goals for this collection was to create an abstract "painting space" and develop a painterly visual language, and then treat the outputs like I would treat a running series of paintings; exploring and working through all the ideas, within certain constraints, trying to exhaust every possibility.

I wanted the outputs to look like they were created by hand, with soft edges and manual imperfections. Colors are deliberately "mis-registered" and shapes/lines are subtly askew. The "Viscosity" feature turns emergent moiré patterns into flattened, solid forms, and renders them as if they were painted with watercolors, or stamped with bleeding inks.


The composition of each piece is mostly determined by five main components:

1. Layers of repeating lines at various angles and spacing, which often overlap and interact to create complex moiré patterns (Kumano Layers)

2. A "Horizon" section that creates a foreground space and a horizon line, bringing the piece into a painterly landscape space

3. Bold caution stripes of various color, thickness, opacity, and orientation

4. Floating "Satellite" shapes that sometimes appear, evoking moons or man-made objects hovering in space

5. A special mix of "Viscosity" and "Erosion" that makes the paint bleed, congeal, and dissolve in unpredictable ways


The overarching color story of each piece is determined by a few interrelated palettes:

- Ten possible Background Colors
- Eight possible palettes for the layered lines (Kumano Palette)
- Eight possible colors of Caution Stripes
- Six possible colors for the Horizon/Foreground layer

When applied in combination and then run through the Viscosity and/or Erosion filters, the breadth of color possibilities is enormous, but always remains connected and coherent.


The algorithm's compositional structure also shows extreme variety, from highly complex to super clean, minimal, and subtle. Everything in the artwork is generated directly from the p5.js script; no external inputs, filters, or images are used.


These pieces are best viewed at large scale in order to appreciate the fine details and nuance. To save a high-res version, just type "S" on your keyboard and a high-res PNG will be generated and downloaded. This can take some time, so please be patient while it renders in the background. In most browsers the high-res output will be 5000 x 6250px (31+ megapixels).

metadata.name: 0xSiebe #14
metadata.description: 0xSiebe is a series exploring gradients, layers and grids. It builds on my ever evolving grid framework and it is my first collection that makes use of shaders. Inspiration I got from artists like Martin Grasser and from my general fascination of light and soft colors.

metadata.name: BETWEEN #41
metadata.description:
Between thought and embodiment.
A color that is not perceived by the human eye - is a radio wave. 
A structure that we cannot yet see, but it already exists - is a building project. 
Information that continues, despite the fact that there is a pause in the ether - is intuition. 
The BETWEEN project is about subtle worlds that are invisible, but always nearby.

This collection has been created with P5.js.
February 2023.
Press 'S' to save a 3375x4725 PNG file.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #365
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: I AM UNFOLDING #148
metadata.description:
In the past, I was but fragments
Rough and jagged
Indefinitely, I weathered and grew
A sculpture formed, unstructured

In the present, I am the precipice
A grandiose monolith
My angles sharp, my lines precise
A work of art, restructured

The future looms before
A blank formlessness yet to be
My function undefined
In perpetuity, unfolding

-----------------------------------------

Best efforts have been made to optimize this project; however, for best performance, a machine with a dedicated GPU is recommended. Viewing the project in live mode is also recommended.

S - export a high resolution image.
P - pause the animation.

metadata.name: Element #94
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.
